  "query": "What are the documented benefits and drawbacks of reducing tillage intensity on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Thirty-four studies from nine European countries found that reducing tillage had positive effects on earthworms, some invertebrates, weeds, and farmland birds (126). These positive effects included increased biomass, species richness, or abundance of earthworms, greater abundance of some invertebrates, increased numbers of some weeds and/or weed species, and higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying date, and shorter foraging distances on reduced tillage fields (126). Additionally, a greater abundance of some birds, including Eurasian skylark, seed-eating songbirds, and gamebirds, was observed in late winter on non-inversion or conservation tillage (126). A review also found that tillage had negative effects on invertebrate numbers and no-till systems had more invertebrate bird food resources (126).\n\nHowever, twenty-six studies from nine European countries found that reducing tillage had either negative, no effect, or no consistent effects on the abundance, biomass, or species richness of some invertebrates, earthworms, and some bird species (126). There were also no consistent effects on the number of different plant species found as seeds, the number of some weed species, and mammal abundance (126). One study found that bird preferences for conservation tillage fields decreased over time, and two studies found that crop type affected the number of weeds under different tillage regimes (126). Long-term studies on earthworms (after ten years) showed conflicting results; one study found higher earthworm biomass under reduced tillage, while another found earthworm abundance was the same between conventional and reduced tillage plots (126). Three of the studies did not distinguish between the effects of reducing tillage and reduced pesticide and/or fertilizer inputs (126). No evidence was found for the effects of reduced tillage on amphibian populations (789), and no studies evaluated the effects of managing tillage practices on reptile populations (3488).",
